Incomplete Crawls

g <- aggregate(rev$link, list(rev$company), function(x) length(unique(x)))
g$from_raw <- raw$pages_to_scrape[match(g$Group.1, raw$company)] + 1
g$perc_done <- g$x*100/g$from_raw

We were talking about that quirk in the sorting of firms on GD. I wanted to look at the distribution of completion percentages. 76.47% of firms are 100% complete. 96.55% of firms are greater than 80% complete. I also generated an empirical CDF of % Complete.

Sub-ratings

Below are relative frequency trends for different sub-rating groups. The first plot is the total number of stars. The vertical line denotes May 22nd 2012. This is when GD 1) adds a 5th subcategory (culture and values) and 2) removes the ability to rate subcateogies with half stars. I think I would like to spend some time poking around that cutoff. There is an exogenous shock to company ratings on GD, which we might be able to leverage in an RDD framework. Anyway, throughout the sample, we see pretty different trends in 5 star ratings compared to other ratings.

library("scales")
star_percent <- function(col_name){
  
  lim <- TRUE
  s1 <- as.data.frame(table(rev[lim,c(col_name)], floor_date(rev$timestamp1[lim], "month")))
  s1$Var1 <- as.character(s1$Var1)
  s1$Var2 <- ymd(as.character(s1$Var2))
  s2 <- aggregate(s1$Freq, list(s1$Var2), sum)
  s1$tot <- s2$x[match(s1$Var2, s2$Group.1)]
  colorz <- c("tomato", "DodgerBlue", "MediumSeaGreen", "gold", "purple", rep("grey", 4))
  numz <- c(1:5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5)
  plot(s1$Var2, s1$Freq/s1$tot,
       col = alpha(colorz[match(s1$Var1, numz)], .25), pch = 19,
       ylim = c(0, .45),
       xlab = "Month", ylab = "Percent of Reviews", main = col_name)
  legend("topright", legend = c(5:1, "Halfs"),
         pch = 19, col = c("purple", "gold", "MediumSeaGreen", "DodgerBlue", "tomato", "grey"),
         bty = "n", ncol = 3)
}

star_percent("stars")
abline(v = ymd("2012-05-22"), lty = 2)
par(mfrow = c(1,1))
star_percent("work_life")
star_percent("career_opportunities")
star_percent("compensation_benefits")
star_percent("senior_management")
star_percent("culture_values")
star_percent("diversity_inclusion")
par(mfrow = c(1,1))

This next set of plots is looking at how prominant missing subratings are. These trends all appears to mirror each other. It looks like if somebody does not fill out one, they do not fill out them all.

miss_percent <- function(col_name){
  
  s1 <- aggregate(is.na(rev[,c(col_name)]), list(floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month")), mean)
  plot(s1$Group.1, 100*s1$x,
       type = "b", pch = 19, main = col_name,
       xlab = "Month", ylab = "Percent Missing",
       col = alpha("black", .33))
}

par(mfrow = c(1,1))

miss_percent("work_life")
miss_percent("career_opportunities")
miss_percent("compensation_benefits")
miss_percent("senior_management")
miss_percent("culture_values")
miss_percent("diversity_inclusion")
par(mfrow = c(1,1))

In the following two plots, I find the percent of reviews that have sub-ratings completely missing or completely filled out.

all_names <- c("work_life",
               "career_opportunities",
               "compensation_benefits",
               "senior_management",
               "culture_values",
               "diversity_inclusion")
m_small <- aggregate(rowSums(is.na(rev[,all_names])), list(floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month")), min)
m_big <- m_small
m_big$x <- 6 - m_small$x

s1 <- aggregate(rowSums(is.na(rev[,all_names])) == m_big$x[match(floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month"), m_big$Group.1)], list(floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month")), mean)

s2 <- aggregate(rowSums(is.na(rev[,all_names])) == m_small$x[match(floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month"), m_small$Group.1)], list(floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month")), mean)

plot(s1$Group.1, s1$x,
     type = "b", pch = 19, main = "",
     xlab = "Month", ylab = "Percent With All Missing Sub-Ratings",
     col = alpha("black", .33))
plot(s2$Group.1, s2$x,
     type = "b", pch = 19, main = "",
     xlab = "Month", ylab = "Percent With No Missing Sub-Ratings",
     col = alpha("black", .33))

This is a plot showing the proportion of reviews where N sub-ratings are filled out. Please keep in mind that the number of sub-ratings possible changes from 4 to 5 (2012-05-22) to 6 (2020-08-26). Until 2012-05-22, every review has all 4 sub-categories filled out. Then, until ~2020, over 80% of reviews have all 5 categories filled out.

tab <- table(rowSums(is.na(rev[,all_names])), floor_date(rev$timestamp1, "month"))
tab <- as.data.frame(tab)
tab1 <- aggregate(tab$Freq, list(tab$Var2), sum)
tab$relFreq <- tab$Freq*100/tab1$x[match(tab$Var2, tab1$Group.1)]
tab$Var2 <- ymd(as.character(tab$Var2))
tab$Var1 <- as.numeric(as.character(tab$Var1))
